<TEXT>
university officials are investigating 
allegations that an 11yearold boy who became the youngest person 
to graduate from college was allowed to take a staggering course 
load that one authority called unconscionable 
in some of his classes at the university of california at santa 
cruz adragon de mello was struggling to just pass according to a 
report published sunday the boy received a degree in computational 
mathematics last year 
adragons advisers should have been concerned by the pressures 
on him his often mediocre work and the high number of waivers and 
grade changes he received said uc santa cruz vicechancellor 
isebill gruhn 
the college advising system apparently let him down she 
said in sundays editions of the santa cruz sentinel which 
obtained copies of adragons transcripts evaluations and other 
university documents 
after viewing the documents last week gruhn called the boys 
course load unconscionable 
uc santa cruz chancellor robert stevens said friday that his 
office will investigate the handling of the boys academic career 
adragon made national headlines and became an entry in the 
guinness book of world records when he graduated last june 
his father agustin de mello defended his sons academic record 
any negative evaluations of his sons work were written by 
people who were prejudiced against the boy said de mello the 
father had drawn up plans for raising a boy genius including 
advanced degrees and a nobel prize by age 16 even before adragon 
was conceived 
it was the university de mello said that placed all the 
pressure on his son to take so many classes that was because the 
family could not get the kind of financial aid to support two years 
of study instead of one he said 
according to university records cited by the paper adragon took 
a double load of classes and often used petitions and waivers to 
win exceptions from ucs usual requirements 
and while adragon did well in some mathematics and computer 
classes he struggled in others his performance in one astronomy 
course was the poorest of anyones in the class and was far below 
the passfail cutoff the instructor wrote in an evaluation 
the source of this stress was probably the fact that 
according to what he told me he was taking six courses this 
quarter wrote the professor merle walker if it is true i 
question why the relevant authorities within the university 
permitted him to do this 
the usual load at the santa cruz campus which issues pass 
or fail grades is three courses per quarter gruhn said it was 
a serious matter for any student to take even four 
adragon on three occasions also did not complete his course work 
by the end of the term and petitioned to have the grades changed to 
pass after completing makeup work 
</TEXT>
