ethnic minority groups within the burma 
communist party insurgency have rebelled against the party 
leadership and seized control of its national headquarters a 
stateowned newspaper said sunday 
the working peoples daily said forces made up of persons from 
national racial groups could not bear the domination of the 
party in their political military and economic affairs and the 
conflict between them grew 
it said the rebellious members captured the party headquarters 
in pangsang about 415 miles northeast of rangoon and the 
northcentral branch office in mongkoe about 125 miles north of 
pangsang both are in shan state 
the newspaper did not say when the rebellion took place 
with 1500020000 fighters the burma communist party is the 
strongest of a dozen guerrilla groups fighting the authoritarian 
government the groups leadership has been dominated by members of 
the ethnic majority the burmese but most of the fighters are from 
minority groups 
government officials said earlier that the wa and the kokang 
ethnic groups recently revolted against the communist leadership 
and this was confirmed sunday by independent sources who traveled 
to the area of fighting 
a source who demanded anonymity said there were reports the 
ethnic groups arrested some communist leaders 
the communists recruited the minorities after taking over their 
areas along the chinese border they have paid them small amounts 
of money to fight mainly in major operations 
the communist insurgency to overthrow the government began 
shortly after burma was granted independence from great britain in 
1948 the party says it stands for democracy but much of its 
financing comes from opium trafficking 
the insurgency has weakened because china has reduced and 
possibly cut off its once significant aid to the communists in 
order to improve relations with the burmese government 
the turmoil within the party comes as the government has 
inflicted major defeats on the karen national union another major 
insurgent group based along the eastern border with thailand 
