since 1970 the year of the first earth day and the dawn of the 
modern environmental movement public attitudes about environmental 
protection have changed dramatically as shown by the result of 
opinion polls cited in the analysis 
here are a few examples 
concern about water and air pollution in 1970 according to a 
gallup poll only 48 percent of those interviewed expressed concern 
about polluted water last year in answer to the same question 84 
percent said they had such worries people who were seriously 
concerned about air pollution increased from 46 percent in 1970 to 
73 percent in 1988 
support for tougher environmental laws and regulations in a 
1977 survey by the roper organization only 27 percent of the 
respondents believed environmental laws and regulations were 
inadequate by 1983 when roper asked the same question 48 percent 
felt that way and last year 53 percent of those interviewed by 
cambridge reports said tougher environmental laws were needed 
spending money on the environment last year 65 percent of the 
respondents to a national opinion research center poll said more 
money should be spent on the environment compared to 48 percent 
who held that view in 1977 a series of roper polls over roughly 
the same time period reflected a somewhat smaller but also 
significant increase 
protecting wilderness in answer to a cambridge reports poll in 
1978 only 19 percent of the respondents chose preserving public 
wilderness areas over opening them for energy development a choice 
of 65 percent in answer to the same question last year 47 percent 
favored preservation compared to 42 percent for development 
greenhouse effect problem surveys by cambridge reports show a 
growing number of people consider global warming as a very 
serious problem in 1982 only 12 percent believed so 24 percent 
in 1986 and 39 percent last year 
a variety of other polls cited by the study also reflect an 
unmistakable shift to a more proenviromental stance says 
david baker chairman of americans for the environment a research 
organization for a variety of environmental and conservation groups 
the message maintains baker is that people are mad as 
hell about the way we treat our environment and they dont want to 
take it anymore 
