<TEXT>
an opposition leader on sunday blasted 
as inadequate a new communications law that abolishes prior 
censorship and indefinite closures of the print and broadcast media 
it is abominable from every point of view erick ramirez 
president of the opposition social christian party said in a 
telephone interview it buries whatever vestige of press freedom 
exists in nicarauga 
ramirez said the new law touted as one of president daniel 
ortegas new democratic reforms fails to authorize private 
television stations something opposition groups have long sought 
instead the new law guarantees equal access to social and 
political groups on governmentrun television 
the association of independent journalists of nicaragua also 
criticized the new law saying it would prevent free expression 
the sandinistacontrolled national assembly approved the law 
friday and ortega signed it into law on saturday 
before leaving for a twoweek tour of europe on saturday ortega 
proclaimed in no other country in the region are there more 
guarantees for jouranlists than in nicargua the rest of central 
america he said has exercised terrorism against journalism 
ortega introduced the law as part of democratic reforms he 
promised to institute in his country following a meeting of the 
five central american presidents in el salvador in feburary 
he also agreed to move up presidential elections by 10 months 
to february 1990 
the presidents of nicaragua el salvador guatemala costa rica 
and honduras additionally agreed to come up by midmay with a plan 
for dismantling the nicarguan rebel force known as the contras 
about 11000 contra rebels along with their families live in 
honduran camps near the nicaraguan border 
the new law establishes sanctions for disseminating information 
deemed contrary to the interests of the state for altering 
government press releases communiques and other statments and for 
the transmission diffusion publication or projection of 
injurious defamatory or false information 
although it abolishes prior censorship and indefinte closure of 
newspapers and broadcast stations the new law will allow the 
interior ministry to order closures of up to four days and gives it 
the power to order an offending broadcaster or publisher to issue a 
retraction clarification or correction 
broadcasters and publishers will have the right to a hearing 
before sanctions are applied 
under previous practice the ministry had the power to order 
indefinite shutdowns without hearings 
the opposition daily la prensa said in an editorial this 
weekend ortega also did not fulfill his promise to allow private 
television broadcasts in nicaragua condemning for always the 
nicaraguan people to state television that transmit the oretegist 
image every minute 
his law which he dares to describe as the best in central 
america continues to contain grave threats to the excercise of 
liberty of expression in nicargua la prensa said 
</TEXT>
